  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, federal contract obligations in Massachusetts total $11.4B. Award activity to date includes 68,405 awards with an average award size of $166K, and obligations fell 41.1% year over year. Historical annual obligations show fluctuations: FY21 totaled $24.2B, FY22 totaled $17.9B, FY23 totaled $18.3B, FY24 totaled $17.8B, FY25 totaled $19.3B, and FY26 totaled $11.4B. The Department of Defense is the single largest buying agency, accounting for $8.6B in obligations in FY2026 to date. Other leading buying agencies include the Department of Veterans Affairs ($699M), the Department of Transportation ($698M), and the Department of Health and Human Services ($404M). Top vendors in FY2026 to date include RAYTHEON COMPANY ($2.1B), GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY ($1.2B), RAYTHEON COMPANY ($995M), and MASSACHUSETTS INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY ($708M). Major industry categories by obligations include Search, Detection, Navigation, Guidance, Aeronautical, and Nautical System and Instrument Manufacturing ($2B) and Engineering Services ($1.4B).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies drive federal contracting activity in Massachusetts?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense drives the largest portion of FY2026 to date contracting in Massachusetts with $8.6B in obligations. The next-largest buyers are the Department of Veterans Affairs ($699M), the Department of Transportation ($698M), and the Department of Health and Human Services ($404M). Additional notable buyers in FY2026 to date include the Department of Homeland Security ($316M) and the Department of the Treasury ($195M)."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which vendors and industries capture the most obligations in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "RAYTHEON COMPANY is the top vendor in FY2026 to date with $2.1B in obligations, followed by GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY ($1.2B) and another RAYTHEON COMPANY entry ($995M). Key industry categories by obligations include Search, Detection, Navigation, Guidance, Aeronautical, and Nautical System and Instrument Manufacturing ($2B) and Engineering Services ($1.4B). Research and development categories and aircraft-related manufacturing also rank among the largest industry recipients."
      }
    ]
